 
<p>
A protist species known as "philaster" was responsible for nearly eliminating
a species of sea
<a href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/apr/24/scientists-discover-why-sea-urchins-are-dying-off-from-us-to-the-caribbean">urchins on the US east coast</a>
and in the Caribbean.
<p>
Is there any chance this organism could be used safely to save
California's kelp forests from the sea urchins that are wiping it out?
That does not automatically follow &mdash; the sea urchins there might be
immune to them, or they might destroy other species too.  Research
would be needed.

